images.alt: A massive, emerald-scaled dragon in a pristine hibachi chef’s uniform—white jacket stretched tight over its muscular frame, black apron singed at the edges—stands behind a gleaming steel grill in a bustling Japanese steakhouse. Its eyes burn with molten fury as it unleashes torrents of blazing orange and blue fire from its fanged maw, searing skewers of meats and vegetables mid-air. The flames curl and whip around the sizzling food, sending sparks and embers cascading across the room. Steam hisses up in great bursts as oils crackle on the grill, the aroma of charred delicacies filling the air.  The customers—wide-eyed and leaning back in their seats—shield themselves from the intense heat, napkins fluttering like flags in the fiery gusts. Wait staff freeze mid-step, their trays trembling, as the dragon’s tail swishes dangerously close to tables. Reflections of the inferno shimmer in the lacquered surfaces and sake glasses. Wisps of smoke coil toward the ceiling fans, partially obscuring paper lanterns swaying from the heat wave.  The entire scene is rendered in ultra-realistic, high-dynamic-range detail, with cinematic depth of field, every scale, droplet of sweat, and wisp of smoke sharply defined. Lighting shifts between the warm, flickering glow of the fire and the cool ambient restaurant lighting, creating a stark visual contrast. The perspective places the viewer at table height, as if part of the startled audience, capturing the raw chaos and heat of the moment.
